Supine hypertension typically occurs when the person's body isn't able to adjust to the change in position, and the pressure of the blood against the veins in the legs is too high. This can lead to a number of health problems, including heart attack, stroke, and kidney failure. Treatment for supine hypertension typically includes medication and lifestyle changes, such as losing weight and increasing exercise.
